{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_011DEPC1Y29scnBcCfwAXuSK","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→/**\n     4→ * AND specification, used to create a new specification that is the AND of two other\n     5→ * specifications.\n     6→ */\n     7→public class AndSpecification<T> extends AbstractSpecification<T> {\n     8→\n     9→  private final Specification<T> spec1;\n    10→  private final Specification<T> spec2;\n    11→\n    12→  /**\n    13→   * Create a new AND specification based on two other spec.\n    14→   *\n    15→   * @param spec1 Specification one.\n    16→   * @param spec2 Specification two.\n    17→   */\n    18→  public AndSpecification(Specification<T> spec1, Specification<T> spec2) {\n    19→    this.spec1 = spec1;\n    20→    this.spec2 = spec2;\n    21→  }\n    22→\n    23→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    24→  @Override\n    25→  public boolean isSatisfiedBy(T t) {\n    26→    return spec1.isSatisfiedBy(t) && spec2.isSatisfiedBy(t);\n    27→  }\n    28→}\n    29→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_011NxFJarYU776gLEHoF8NLa","session_id":"300f1a06-b6cf-43f1-b117-9879dd779de7","uuid":"519fc803-8da1-47c5-b201-90e548783e4e"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_011MKcMKnqa8aVyT8M99PcVj","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→// TODO [Clean Code] Make this a CDI singleton?\n     4→public class DomainObjectUtils {\n     5→\n     6→  /** Prevent instantiation. */\n     7→  private DomainObjectUtils() {}\n     8→\n     9→  /**\n    10→   * @param actual actual value\n    11→   * @param safe a null-safe value\n    12→   * @param <T> type\n    13→   * @return actual value, if it's not null, or safe value if the actual value is null.\n    14→   */\n    15→  public static <T> T nullSafe(T actual, T safe) {\n    16→    return actual == null ? safe : actual;\n    17→  }\n    18→}\n    19→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_011NxFJarYU776gLEHoF8NLa","session_id":"300f1a06-b6cf-43f1-b117-9879dd779de7","uuid":"1e2feba0-59dc-4f6b-8037-c34d63cf84e0"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01XXDGVTehJpguo3AvdUia8Y","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→/** NOT decorator, used to create a new specifcation that is the inverse (NOT) of the given spec. */\n     4→public class NotSpecification<T> extends AbstractSpecification<T> {\n     5→\n     6→  private final Specification<T> spec1;\n     7→\n     8→  /**\n     9→   * Create a new NOT specification based on another spec.\n    10→   *\n    11→   * @param spec1 Specification instance to not.\n    12→   */\n    13→  public NotSpecification(Specification<T> spec1) {\n    14→    this.spec1 = spec1;\n    15→  }\n    16→\n    17→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    18→  @Override\n    19→  public boolean isSatisfiedBy(T t) {\n    20→    return !spec1.isSatisfiedBy(t);\n    21→  }\n    22→}\n    23→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_011NxFJarYU776gLEHoF8NLa","session_id":"300f1a06-b6cf-43f1-b117-9879dd779de7","uuid":"a718f3e8-7470-4db1-886a-dd8ca838c5c8"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01712z4Y4rMDPiTtckg65j1j","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→/**\n     4→ * OR specification, used to create a new specification that is the OR of two other specifications.\n     5→ */\n     6→public class OrSpecification<T> extends AbstractSpecification<T> {\n     7→\n     8→  private final Specification<T> spec1;\n     9→  private final Specification<T> spec2;\n    10→\n    11→  /**\n    12→   * Create a new OR specification based on two other spec.\n    13→   *\n    14→   * @param spec1 Specification one.\n    15→   * @param spec2 Specification two.\n    16→   */\n    17→  public OrSpecification(Specification<T> spec1, Specification<T> spec2) {\n    18→    this.spec1 = spec1;\n    19→    this.spec2 = spec2;\n    20→  }\n    21→\n    22→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    23→  @Override\n    24→  public boolean isSatisfiedBy(T t) {\n    25→    return spec1.isSatisfiedBy(t) || spec2.isSatisfiedBy(t);\n    26→  }\n    27→}\n    28→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_011NxFJarYU776gLEHoF8NLa","session_id":"300f1a06-b6cf-43f1-b117-9879dd779de7","uuid":"c343e8d0-4c36-4cd2-b7bf-b3e0f5e5932a"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01SsFbcfwT1UvWnkXyaiwsnf","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→/**\n     4→ * Specification interface.\n     5→ *\n     6→ * <p>Use {@link AbstractSpecification} as base for creating specifications, and only the method\n     7→ * {@link #isSatisfiedBy(Object)} must be implemented.\n     8→ */\n     9→public interface Specification<T> {\n    10→\n    11→  /**\n    12→   * Check if {@code t} is satisfied by the specification.\n    13→   *\n    14→   * @param t Object to test.\n    15→   * @return {@code true} if {@code t} satisfies the specification.\n    16→   */\n    17→  boolean isSatisfiedBy(T t);\n    18→\n    19→  /**\n    20→   * Create a new specification that is the AND operation of {@code this} specification and another\n    21→   * specification.\n    22→   *\n    23→   * @param specification Specification to AND.\n    24→   * @return A new specification.\n    25→   */\n    26→  Specification<T> and(Specification<T> specification);\n    27→\n    28→  /**\n    29→   * Create a new specification that is the OR operation of {@code this} specification and another\n    30→   * specification.\n    31→   *\n    32→   * @param specification Specification to OR.\n    33→   * @return A new specification.\n    34→   */\n    35→  Specification<T> or(Specification<T> specification);\n    36→\n    37→  /**\n    38→   * Create a new specification that is the NOT operation of {@code this} specification.\n    39→   *\n    40→   * @param specification Specification to NOT.\n    41→   * @return A new specification.\n    42→   */\n    43→  Specification<T> not(Specification<T> specification);\n    44→}\n    45→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_011NxFJarYU776gLEHoF8NLa","session_id":"300f1a06-b6cf-43f1-b117-9879dd779de7","uuid":"163485c3-ecc4-44d8-ae09-8a118b60f04d"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01G9G4HHuCkBpsALA8jLgkdn","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have successfully read all Java source files in the interfaces directory and its subdirectories. Let me provide you with a comprehensive summary of all the files and their full contents.\n\n## Complete Summary of All Java Files in the interfaces/ Directory\n\nI have read **41 Java source files** from the `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/interfaces/` directory and all its subdirectories. Here is the complete organization:\n\n### Root Level (interfaces/)\n1. **FacesConfiguration.java** - Jakarta Faces configuration using JSF 2.3\n2. **Coordinates.java** - DTO for latitude/longitude coordinates\n3. **CoordinatesFactory.java** - Factory for creating coordinates for various locations\n\n### Booking Package (interfaces/booking/)\n\n#### Facade (facade/)\n4. **BookingServiceFacade.java** - Interface defining booking operations (bookNewCargo, assignCargoToRoute, changeDestination, etc.)\n\n#### Facade Internal (facade/internal/)\n5. **DefaultBookingServiceFacade.java** - Implementation of BookingServiceFacade with CDI injections\n\n#### Facade DTOs (facade/dto/)\n6. **TrackingEvents.java** - DTO for tracking events with description, time, and expected status\n7. **RouteCandidate.java** - DTO for itinerary candidates with legs\n8. **CargoRoute.java** - DTO for cargo routing with origin, destination, deadline, legs\n9. **Location.java** - DTO for location with UN Locode and name\n10. **CargoStatus.java** - DTO for cargo status with tracking info, events, ETA\n11. **Leg.java** - DTO for itinerary leg with voyage, locations, and times\n\n#### Facade Assemblers (facade/internal/assembler/)\n12. **TrackingEventsDtoAssembler.java** - Assembles tracking event DTOs from domain objects\n13. **LocationDtoAssembler.java** - Assembles location DTOs from domain locations\n14. **CargoRouteDtoAssembler.java** - Assembles cargo route DTOs\n15. **ItineraryCandidateDtoAssembler.java** - Assembles and converts itinerary DTOs\n16. **CargoStatusDtoAssembler.java** - Assembles cargo status DTOs with events\n\n#### SSE (sse/)\n17. **LocationViewAdapter.java** - View adapter for displaying locations in real-time tracking\n18. **RealtimeCargoTrackingService.java** - JAX-RS SSE service for real-time cargo tracking\n19. **RealtimeCargoTrackingViewAdapter.java** - View adapter for cargo in real-time context\n\n#### Web (web/)\n20. **ChangeArrivalDeadline.java** - JSF backing bean for changing cargo arrival deadline\n21. **CargoDetails.java** - JSF backing bean for viewing cargo details\n22. **Booking.java** - JSF backing bean for booking flow with location selection\n23. **Track.java** - JSF backing bean for tracking cargo in admin interface\n24. **ChangeDestinationDialog.java** - JSF backing bean for change destination dialog\n25. **ListCargo.java** - JSF backing bean for listing cargos (routed, unrouted, claimed)\n26. **ChangeDestination.java** - JSF backing bean for changing cargo destination\n27. **ItinerarySelection.java** - JSF backing bean for selecting route itineraries\n28. **ChangeArrivalDeadlineDialog.java** - JSF backing bean for arrival deadline dialog\n\n### Handling Package (interfaces/handling/)\n\n29. **HandlingEventRegistrationAttempt.java** - Transfer object for handling event registration attempts\n\n#### Mobile (mobile/)\n30. **EventLogger.java** - JSF backing bean for mobile event logging interface\n\n#### File (file/)\n31. **UploadDirectoryScanner.java** - EJB that periodically scans for event files using batch processing\n32. **LineParseExceptionListener.java** - Batch listener for handling parse errors\n33. **EventItemWriter.java** - Batch item writer for processing event files\n34. **FileProcessorJobListener.java** - Batch job listener for logging\n35. **EventLineParseException.java** - Custom exception for line parsing errors\n36. **EventItemReader.java** - Batch item reader for reading event files\n37. **EventFilesCheckpoint.java** - Checkpoint for batch processing state\n\n#### REST (rest/)\n38. **HandlingReport.java** - Transfer object for REST handling reports with validation\n39. **HandlingReportService.java** - JAX-RS REST endpoint for submitting handling reports\n\n### Tracking Package (interfaces/tracking/)\n\n#### Web (web/)\n40. **Track.java** - JSF backing bean for public cargo tracking interface\n41. **CargoTrackingViewAdapter.java** - View adapter wrapping cargo for tracking display with inner HandlingEventViewAdapter class\n\n---\n\nAll files have been read completely and contain the full source code for the Cargo Tracker application's interface layer, which handles:\n- Web UI (JSF backing beans)\n- REST services\n- Server-Sent Events (SSE) for real-time tracking\n- Batch file processing for handling events\n- DTOs and view adapters for data transfer\n- Facade pattern for shielding domain layer from UI concerns"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"300f1a06-b6cf-43f1-b117-9879dd779de7","uuid":"456e4843-1a7e-4c92-b407-8a9c8cf11aeb"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_011NxFJarYU776gLEHoF8NLa","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have successfully read all 35 Java source files from the Cargo Tracker application's domain model. Below is a comprehensive report of the full contents of each file:\n\n## Domain Model Files - Complete Contents\n\n### Cargo Package (domain/model/cargo/)\n\n#### 1. Cargo.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/cargo/Cargo.java`\n\nThis is the central aggregate root entity (193 lines) that represents a cargo in the system. Key features:\n- Contains TrackingId, origin Location, RouteSpecification, Itinerary, and Delivery\n- Provides methods to specify new routes and assign itineraries\n- Updates delivery progress based on handling history\n- Uses JPA annotations (@Entity, @Embedded, @ManyToOne)\n\n#### 2. CargoRepository.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/cargo/CargoRepository.java`\n\nSimple repository interface (14 lines) with methods:\n- `find(TrackingId)` - Find cargo by tracking ID\n- `findAll()` - Get all cargo\n- `store(Cargo)` - Persist cargo\n- `nextTrackingId()` - Generate next tracking ID\n\n#### 3. Delivery.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/cargo/Delivery.java`\n\nComplex value object (382 lines) representing the actual transportation status:\n- Tracks transport status, routing status, last known location, current voyage\n- Calculates ETA, misdirection status, next expected activity\n- Uses null object pattern with constants like `ETA_UNKOWN` and `NO_ACTIVITY`\n- Implements sophisticated business logic for delivery state calculation\n- Truncates LocalDateTime to seconds as Hibernate workaround\n\n#### 4. HandlingActivity.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/cargo/HandlingActivity.java`\n\nValue object (121 lines) representing expected handling operations:\n- Contains HandlingEvent.Type, Location, and optional Voyage\n- Used to express predictions about future cargo handling\n- Includes `isEmpty()` method to check if activity is defined\n\n#### 5. Itinerary.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/cargo/Itinerary.java`\n\nValue object (166 lines) representing the planned route:\n- Contains an ordered list of Legs\n- Implements null object pattern with `EMPTY_ITINERARY`\n- Validates if handling events are expected based on the itinerary\n- Provides methods to get initial departure, final arrival location and date\n\n#### 6. Leg.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/cargo/Leg.java`\n\nEntity (146 lines) representing one leg of a journey:\n- Contains Voyage, load/unload Locations, and load/unload times\n- Truncates LocalDateTime to seconds for Hibernate compatibility\n- Implements value-based equality\n\n#### 7. RouteSpecification.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/cargo/RouteSpecification.java`\n\nSpecification value object (107 lines) describing cargo requirements:\n- Contains origin, destination, and arrival deadline\n- Extends AbstractSpecification<Itinerary>\n- Validates that origin and destination are different\n- Implements `isSatisfiedBy()` to check if an itinerary meets requirements\n\n#### 8. RoutingStatus.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/cargo/RoutingStatus.java`\n\nSimple enum (11 lines) with three states:\n- NOT_ROUTED - No itinerary assigned\n- ROUTED - Valid itinerary assigned\n- MISROUTED - Itinerary doesn't satisfy route specification\n\n#### 9. TrackingId.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/cargo/TrackingId.java`\n\nValue object (58 lines) for unique cargo identification:\n- Embeddable with unique constraint\n- Provides `getIdString()` for string representation\n- Implements value-based equality\n\n#### 10. TransportStatus.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/cargo/TransportStatus.java`\n\nEnum (13 lines) with five transport states:\n- NOT_RECEIVED\n- IN_PORT\n- ONBOARD_CARRIER\n- CLAIMED\n- UNKNOWN\n\n### Handling Package (domain/model/handling/)\n\n#### 11. HandlingEvent.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/handling/HandlingEvent.java`\n\nAggregate root entity (305 lines) for cargo handling events:\n- Contains Type enum (LOAD, UNLOAD, RECEIVE, CLAIM, CUSTOMS)\n- Tracks cargo, location, completion time, registration time, and optional voyage\n- Type enum enforces whether voyage is required/prohibited\n- Validates that voyage requirements match event type\n- Truncates times to seconds for Hibernate\n\n#### 12. HandlingEventFactory.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/handling/HandlingEventFactory.java`\n\nApplication-scoped factory (95 lines) for creating HandlingEvents:\n- Injects CargoRepository, VoyageRepository, LocationRepository\n- Validates cargo, voyage, and location exist\n- Throws specific exceptions for unknown entities\n- Creates appropriate HandlingEvent based on parameters\n\n#### 13. HandlingEventRepository.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/handling/HandlingEventRepository.java`\n\nSimple repository interface (10 lines):\n- `store(HandlingEvent)` - Persist event\n- `lookupHandlingHistoryOfCargo(TrackingId)` - Get handling history\n\n#### 14. HandlingHistory.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/handling/HandlingHistory.java`\n\nValue object (76 lines) wrapping a collection of HandlingEvents:\n- Implements null object pattern with `EMPTY`\n- Provides sorted, distinct events by completion time\n- Returns most recently completed event\n- Filters duplicates using HashSet\n\n#### 15. CannotCreateHandlingEventException.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/handling/CannotCreateHandlingEventException.java`\n\nChecked exception (23 lines):\n- Annotated with @ApplicationException(rollback = true)\n- Base exception for handling event creation failures\n- Used when event cannot be created from given parameters\n\n#### 16. UnknownCargoException.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/handling/UnknownCargoException.java`\n\nSpecific exception (22 lines):\n- Extends CannotCreateHandlingEventException\n- Thrown when tracking ID doesn't exist\n- Provides descriptive error message with tracking ID\n\n#### 17. UnknownLocationException.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/handling/UnknownLocationException.java`\n\nSpecific exception (19 lines):\n- Extends CannotCreateHandlingEventException\n- Thrown when UN Locode doesn't exist\n- Provides descriptive error message with locode\n\n#### 18. UnknownVoyageException.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/handling/UnknownVoyageException.java`\n\nSpecific exception (20 lines):\n- Extends CannotCreateHandlingEventException\n- Thrown when voyage number doesn't exist\n- Provides descriptive error message with voyage number\n\n### Location Package (domain/model/location/)\n\n#### 19. Location.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/location/Location.java`\n\nEntity (99 lines) representing locations:\n- Identified by UN Locode\n- Contains location name\n- Implements null object pattern with `UNKNOWN` location\n- Uses named queries for finding by locode\n\n#### 20. LocationRepository.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/location/LocationRepository.java`\n\nSimple repository interface (10 lines):\n- `find(UnLocode)` - Find location by UN Locode\n- `findAll()` - Get all locations\n\n#### 21. SampleLocations.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/location/SampleLocations.java`\n\nTest data class (19 lines) with 13 predefined locations:\n- Major cities like Hong Kong, Melbourne, Stockholm, Helsinki, Chicago, Tokyo, Hamburg, Shanghai, Rotterdam, Gothenburg, Hangzhou, New York, Dallas\n- Each with proper UN Locode\n\n#### 22. UnLocode.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/location/UnLocode.java`\n\nValue object (77 lines) for UN Location Code:\n- Validates format: 2 letters + 3 alphanumeric (2-9)\n- Automatically converts to uppercase\n- Embeddable with validation annotations\n- Pattern: [a-zA-Z]{2}[a-zA-Z2-9]{3}\n\n### Voyage Package (domain/model/voyage/)\n\n#### 23. CarrierMovement.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/voyage/CarrierMovement.java`\n\nEntity (120 lines) representing vessel voyage segment:\n- Contains departure/arrival locations and times\n- Implements null object pattern with `NONE`\n- Truncates times to seconds for Hibernate\n- Value-based equality\n\n#### 24. SampleVoyages.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/voyage/SampleVoyages.java`\n\nTest data class (301 lines) with predefined voyages:\n- Contains 16 sample voyages (CM001-CM006, v100-v400, HONGKONG_TO_NEW_YORK, etc.)\n- Uses reflection to build ALL map\n- Provides lookup methods\n- Complex multi-leg journeys with realistic schedules\n\n#### 25. Schedule.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/voyage/Schedule.java`\n\nValue object (72 lines) for voyage schedule:\n- Contains ordered list of CarrierMovements\n- Implements null object pattern with `EMPTY`\n- Validates non-empty carrier movements\n- Provides unmodifiable list view\n\n#### 26. Voyage.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/voyage/Voyage.java`\n\nEntity (123 lines) representing a voyage:\n- Contains VoyageNumber and Schedule\n- Implements null object pattern with `NONE`\n- Includes Builder pattern for incremental construction\n- Builder adds movements and chains departure/arrival locations\n\n#### 27. VoyageNumber.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/voyage/VoyageNumber.java`\n\nValue object (64 lines) for voyage identification:\n- Embeddable with validation\n- Provides `getIdString()` for string representation\n- Value-based equality\n\n#### 28. VoyageRepository.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/model/voyage/VoyageRepository.java`\n\nSimple repository interface (10 lines):\n- `find(VoyageNumber)` - Find voyage by number\n- `findAll()` - Get all voyages\n\n### Domain Service Package (domain/service/)\n\n#### 29. RoutingService.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/service/RoutingService.java`\n\nDomain service interface (15 lines):\n- Single method: `fetchRoutesForSpecification(RouteSpecification)`\n- Returns list of possible itineraries\n- May return empty list if no routes found\n\n### Shared Package (domain/shared/)\n\n#### 30. AbstractSpecification.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/shared/AbstractSpecification.java`\n\nAbstract base class (30 lines) for Specification pattern:\n- Implements composite operations: and(), or(), not()\n- Subclasses only need to implement `isSatisfiedBy()`\n- Generic type T for flexibility\n\n#### 31. AndSpecification.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/shared/AndSpecification.java`\n\nSpecification combinator (28 lines):\n- Combines two specifications with AND logic\n- Satisfied only if both specs are satisfied\n\n#### 32. DomainObjectUtils.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/shared/DomainObjectUtils.java`\n\nUtility class (18 lines):\n- Provides `nullSafe()` method for null object pattern\n- Returns actual value if not null, otherwise returns safe default\n- Private constructor prevents instantiation\n\n#### 33. NotSpecification.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/shared/NotSpecification.java`\n\nSpecification decorator (22 lines):\n- Inverts a specification with NOT logic\n- Satisfied when wrapped spec is not satisfied\n\n#### 34. OrSpecification.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/shared/OrSpecification.java`\n\nSpecification combinator (27 lines):\n- Combines two specifications with OR logic\n- Satisfied if either spec is satisfied\n\n#### 35. Specification.java\n**Path:** `/home/bmcginn/git/scarf-latest/scarbench-evals/final/prompt_claude__whole_applications__cargotracker__jakarta__quarkus/run_1/output/src/main/java/org/eclipse/cargotracker/domain/shared/Specification.java`\n\nInterface (44 lines) for Specification pattern:\n- Defines `isSatisfiedBy(T)` contract\n- Declares and(), or(), not() operations\n- Generic type T for testing any object type\n\n## Summary\n\nThis is a comprehensive Domain-Driven Design implementation of a cargo tracking system with:\n- **3 main aggregates:** Cargo, HandlingEvent, and supporting entities\n- **Rich domain model** with extensive business logic in entities and value objects\n- **Specification pattern** for flexible business rules\n- **Null object pattern** throughout (EMPTY, NONE, UNKNOWN constants)\n- **Repository pattern** for persistence abstraction\n- **Factory pattern** for complex object creation\n- **JPA/Hibernate** persistence with validation annotations\n- **Workarounds** for Hibernate LocalDateTime precision issues\n\nThe code demonstrates clean architecture principles, with the domain layer completely independent of infrastructure concerns."}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"300f1a06-b6cf-43f