{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01DKnNc4JuvEx5PPNNGDzy53","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.model.location;\n     2→\n     3→import java.io.Serializable;\n     4→import javax.persistence.Embedded;\n     5→import javax.persistence.Entity;\n     6→import javax.persistence.GeneratedValue;\n     7→import javax.persistence.Id;\n     8→import javax.persistence.NamedQuery;\n     9→import javax.validation.constraints.NotEmpty;\n    10→import javax.validation.constraints.NotNull;\n    11→import org.apache.commons.lang3.Validate;\n    12→\n    13→/**\n    14→ * A location in our model is stops on a journey, such as cargo origin or destination, or carrier\n    15→ * movement end points.\n    16→ *\n    17→ * <p>It is uniquely identified by a UN location code.\n    18→ */\n    19→@Entity\n    20→@NamedQuery(name = \"Location.findAll\", query = \"Select l from Location l\")\n    21→@NamedQuery(\n    22→    name = \"Location.findByUnLocode\",\n    23→    query = \"Select l from Location l where l.unLocode = :unLocode\")\n    24→public class Location implements Serializable {\n    25→\n    26→  private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;\n    27→\n    28→  // Special Location object that marks an unknown location.\n    29→  public static final Location UNKNOWN = new Location(new UnLocode(\"XXXXX\"), \"Unknown location\");\n    30→\n    31→  @Id @GeneratedValue private Long id;\n    32→  @Embedded @NotNull private UnLocode unLocode;\n    33→  @NotEmpty private String name;\n    34→\n    35→  public Location() {\n    36→    // Nothing to do.\n    37→  }\n    38→\n    39→  /**\n    40→   * @param unLocode UN Locode\n    41→   * @param name Location name\n    42→   * @throws IllegalArgumentException if the UN Locode or name is null\n    43→   */\n    44→  public Location(UnLocode unLocode, String name) {\n    45→    Validate.notNull(unLocode);\n    46→    Validate.notNull(name);\n    47→\n    48→    this.unLocode = unLocode;\n    49→    this.name = name;\n    50→  }\n    51→\n    52→  /** @return UN location code for this location. */\n    53→  public UnLocode getUnLocode() {\n    54→    return unLocode;\n    55→  }\n    56→\n    57→  /** @return Actual name of this location, e.g. \"Stockholm\". */\n    58→  public String getName() {\n    59→    return name;\n    60→  }\n    61→\n    62→  /**\n    63→   * @param object to compare\n    64→   * @return Since this is an entiy this will be true iff UN locodes are equal.\n    65→   */\n    66→  @Override\n    67→  public boolean equals(Object object) {\n    68→    if (object == null) {\n    69→      return false;\n    70→    }\n    71→\n    72→    if (this == object) {\n    73→      return true;\n    74→    }\n    75→\n    76→    if (!(object instanceof Location)) {\n    77→      return false;\n    78→    }\n    79→\n    80→    Location other = (Location) object;\n    81→\n    82→    return sameIdentityAs(other);\n    83→  }\n    84→\n    85→  public boolean sameIdentityAs(Location other) {\n    86→    return this.unLocode.sameValueAs(other.unLocode);\n    87→  }\n    88→\n    89→  /** @return Hash code of UN locode. */\n    90→  @Override\n    91→  public int hashCode() {\n    92→    return unLocode.hashCode();\n    93→  }\n    94→\n    95→  @Override\n    96→  public String toString() {\n    97→    return name + \" [\" + unLocode + \"]\";\n    98→  }\n    99→}\n   100→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01JiL5SvGtBZ5fhmV7xK3xs4","session_id":"300f1a06-b6cf-43f1-b117-9879dd779de7","uuid":"1433cc52-8649-4a1e-be97-52a5aadc6bee"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01VPhwNiiUnNAqkB2hnS5k9M","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.model.location;\n     2→\n     3→import java.util.List;\n     4→\n     5→public interface LocationRepository {\n     6→\n     7→  Location find(UnLocode unLocode);\n     8→\n     9→  List<Location> findAll();\n    10→}\n    11→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01JiL5SvGtBZ5fhmV7xK3xs4","session_id":"300f1a06-b6cf-43f1-b117-9879dd779de7","uuid":"5b15c0cc-a991-4a77-8194-7fa790caf3a2"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018N5WYShtqNKZaUyYMmqG4Y","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→/**\n     4→ * Specification interface.\n     5→ *\n     6→ * <p>Use {@link AbstractSpecification} as base for creating specifications, and only the method\n     7→ * {@link #isSatisfiedBy(Object)} must be implemented.\n     8→ */\n     9→public interface Specification<T> {\n    10→\n    11→  /**\n    12→   * Check if {@code t} is satisfied by the specification.\n    13→   *\n    14→   * @param t Object to test.\n    15→   * @return {@code true} if {@code t} satisfies the specification.\n    16→   */\n    17→  boolean isSatisfiedBy(T t);\n    18→\n    19→  /**\n    20→   * Create a new specification that is the AND operation of {@code this} specification and another\n    21→   * specification.\n    22→   *\n    23→   * @param specification Specification to AND.\n    24→   * @return A new specification.\n    25→   */\n    26→  Specification<T> and(Specification<T> specification);\n    27→\n    28→  /**\n    29→   * Create a new specification that is the OR operation of {@code this} specification and another\n    30→   * specification.\n    31→   *\n    32→   * @param specification Specification to OR.\n    33→   * @return A new specification.\n    34→   */\n    35→  Specification<T> or(Specification<T> specification);\n    36→\n    37→  /**\n    38→   * Create a new specification that is the NOT operation of {@code this} specification.\n    39→   *\n    40→   * @param specification Specification to NOT.\n    41→   * @return A new specification.\n    42→   */\n    43→  Specification<T> not(Specification<T> specification);\n    44→}\n    45→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01JiL5SvGtBZ5fhmV7xK3xs4","session_id":"300f1a06-b6cf-43f1-b117-9879dd779de7","uuid":"b4fc5049-c6db-43f1-9136-10329a1540f9"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01CDEQhpokacZwGc8aosnPjy","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→/**\n     4→ * OR specification, used to create a new specification that is the OR of two other specifications.\n     5→ */\n     6→public class OrSpecification<T> extends AbstractSpecification<T> {\n     7→\n     8→  private final Specification<T> spec1;\n     9→  private final Specification<T> spec2;\n    10→\n    11→  /**\n    12→   * Create a new OR specification based on two other spec.\n    13→   *\n    14→   * @param spec1 Specification one.\n    15→   * @param spec2 Specification two.\n    16→   */\n    17→  public OrSpecification(Specification<T> spec1, Specification<T> spec2) {\n    18→    this.spec1 = spec1;\n    19→    this.spec2 = spec2;\n    20→  }\n    21→\n    22→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    23→  @Override\n    24→  public boolean isSatisfiedBy(T t) {\n    25→    return spec1.isSatisfiedBy(t) || spec2.isSatisfiedBy(t);\n    26→  }\n    27→}\n    28→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01JiL5SvGtBZ5fhmV7xK3xs4","session_id":"300f1a06-b6cf-43f1-b117-9879dd779de7","uuid":"b7f54962-e344-4d77-a562-6dcc39a24447"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01JhELV1vM86v1aJ1Jx8hrFU","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→/** NOT decorator, used to create a new specifcation that is the inverse (NOT) of the given spec. */\n     4→public class NotSpecification<T> extends AbstractSpecification<T> {\n     5→\n     6→  private final Specification<T> spec1;\n     7→\n     8→  /**\n     9→   * Create a new NOT specification based on another spec.\n    10→   *\n    11→   * @param spec1 Specification instance to not.\n    12→   */\n    13→  public NotSpecification(Specification<T> spec1) {\n    14→    this.spec1 = spec1;\n    15→  }\n    16→\n    17→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    18→  @Override\n    19→  public boolean isSatisfiedBy(T t) {\n    20→    return !spec1.isSatisfiedBy(t);\n    21→  }\n    22→}\n    23→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01JiL5SvGtBZ5fhmV7xK3xs4","session_id":"300f1a06-b6cf-43f1-b117-9879dd779de7","uuid":"6fdb5736-9b28-4951-a4f1-e48b91296246"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01XBJ6iG3x6wMDCHQYr66H9A","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→/**\n     4→ * AND specification, used to create a new specification that is the AND of two other\n     5→ * specifications.\n     6→ */\n     7→public class AndSpecification<T> extends AbstractSpecification<T> {\n     8→\n     9→  private final Specification<T> spec1;\n    10→  private final Specification<T> spec2;\n    11→\n    12→  /**\n    13→   * Create a new AND specification based on two other spec.\n    14→   *\n    15→   * @param spec1 Specification one.\n    16→   * @param spec2 Specification two.\n    17→   */\n    18→  public AndSpecification(Specification<T> spec1, Specification<T> spec2) {\n    19→    this.spec1 = spec1;\n    20→    this.spec2 = spec2;\n    21→  }\n    22→\n    23→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    24→  @Override\n    25→  public boolean isSatisfiedBy(T t) {\n    26→    return spec1.isSatisfiedBy(t) && spec2.isSatisfiedBy(t);\n    27→  }\n    28→}\n    29→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01JiL5SvGtBZ5fhmV7xK3xs4","session_id":"300f1a06-b6cf-43f1-b117-9879dd779de7","uuid":"db1f2d41-a13e-4040-9502-da25ee47ef7e"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01LtFXJWk1pJQaV2YPhnDAa8","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→// TODO [Clean Code] Make this a CDI singleton?\n     4→public class DomainObjectUtils {\n     5→\n     6→  /** Prevent instantiation. */\n     7→  private DomainObjectUtils() {}\n     8→\n     9→  /**\n    10→   * @param actual actual value\n    11→   * @param safe a null-safe value\n    12→   * @param <T> type\n    13→   * @return actual value, if it's not null, or safe value if the actual value is null.\n    14→   */\n    15→  public static <T> T nullSafe(T actual, T safe) {\n    16→    return actual == null ? safe : actual;\n    17→  }\n    18→}\n    19→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01JiL5SvGtBZ5fhmV7xK3xs4","session_id":"300f1a06-b6cf-43f1-b117-9879dd779de7","uuid":"0344859b-2761-4e02-967a-bbb2ca8dfacf"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_011JSoNBuiJCmw7e4jsf5vgb","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package org.eclipse.cargotracker.domain.shared;\n     2→\n     3→/**\n     4→ * Abstract base implementation of composite {@link Specification} with default implementations for\n     5→ * {@code and}, {@code or} and {@code not}.\n     6→ */\n     7→public abstract class AbstractSpecification<T> implements Specification<T> {\n     8→\n     9→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    10→  @Override\n    11→  public abstract boolean isSatisfiedBy(T t);\n    12→\n    13→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    14→  @Override\n    15→  public Specification<T> and(Specification<T> specification) {\n    16→    return new AndSpecification<>(this, specification);\n    17→  }\n    18→\n    19→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    20→  @Override\n    21→  public Specification<T> or(Specification<T> specification) {\n    22→    return new OrSpecification<>(this, specification);\n    23→  }\n    24→\n    25→  /** {@inheritDoc} */\n    26→  @Override\n    27→  public Specification<T> not(Specification<T> specification) {\n    28→    return new NotSpecification<>(specification);\n    29→  }\n    30→}\n    31→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01JiL5SvGtBZ5fhmV7xK3xs4","session_id":"300f1a06-b6cf-43f1-b117-9879dd779de7","uuid":"6023cb35-ef48-4b3b-a244-b0aebc64f2ad"}
